Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @Carrot{1}, then slice into 0.5cm thick rounds (no need to peel).

Trim the @Pak Choi{1}, then separate the leaves. Cut any larger leaves in half
lengthways down the middle.

Zest and quarter the @Lime{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{1%drizzle} in a #large saucepan{} on high heat.

Once hot, add the carrot and stir-fry until tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Lower the heat to medium and add the @Red Thai Style Paste{50%grams},
@Thai Style Spice Mix{1%sachet} and garlic.

> Add less Thai Style Spice Mix if you'd prefer things milder.

Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @Coconut Milk{180%milliliter}, @Soy Sauce{15%milliliter},
@Sugar{1%tsp} and @Water{150%milliliter} to the carrot.

Stir to combine, bring to the boil and simmer until thickened slightly,
~{5-6%minutes}.

While your laksa simmers, heat a drizzle of @oil{1%drizzle} in a #large frying
pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @Chicken Gyozas{1%pack} and fry until golden on the bottom,
~{2-3%minutes}. Reduce the heat to medium-low, add @Water{1%tbsp} to the pan and
immediately cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}.

Cook until the gyozas are piping hot, ~{3-4%minutes}. Remove from the heat.

Add the @Udon Noodles{220%grams} and pak choi leaves to your laksa and simmer
until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the lime zest and a squeeze of lime juice.

Taste and add more @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste}, lime juice and sugar if
needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick - you want a soupy
consistency!

Share the udon laksa between your #bowls{}.

Top with the chicken gyozas.

Serve with any remaining lime wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!